Wyclif also shows that liberty is destroyed to a great extent by the rules of the sects; a point to which he returns in the last chapter (pp. 280 and seq). And as, notwithstanding his Deter- minism, he is a strong upholder of individual free-will, this is a very important thing with him. It would here be irrelevant to show how his system reconciles free-will and Determinism (Omnia que eveniunt, de necessitate eveniunt)‚· it would also take far too much space3 but the working out of his system appears clearly in his philosophical works, ofwhich I have had the occasion to copy some, and to collate others.
